Synchronous and asynchronous programming are two different ways of handling code execution in JavaScript. In synchronous programming, code is executed in a linear manner, from top to bottom, and the program waits for each operation to complete before moving on to the next. This can lead to issues such as blocking the main thread and causing the application to become unresponsive if an operation takes a long time to complete.

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows the code to continue executing without waiting for every operation to finish. This is achieved by using callbacks, promises, or async/await, which allow the program to handle multiple tasks concurrently and maintain responsiveness.

An example of synchronous programming:
```javascript
function syncExample() {
  // Synchronous operation that may take a long time to complete
  for (let i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
    console.log(i);
  }
}

syncExample();
```

In this example, the loop will block the main thread and the program will be unresponsive until it finishes executing.

An example of asynchronous programming:
```javascript
function asyncExample() {
  // Asynchronous operation using a setTimeout function
  setTimeout(() => {
    for (let i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
      console.log(i);
    }
  }, 0);
}

asyncExample();
```

In this example, the `setTimeout` function ensures that the loop is executed asynchronously and does not block the main thread. The program remains responsive and the loop will be executed after a delay of 0 milliseconds.

